Rating: 4
Sweet and sour..to make this into a sweet and sour, substitute brown sugar for the honey, chicken broth for the water. Add 2 TBSP fresh ginger with garlic, 1 can drained pineapple tidbits, 3 TBsp vinegar, 1/4 c of the pineapple juice, stir into it, 2 TBsp cornstarch to thicken (use more or less of this mixture, till desired consistency)

Rating: 3
I made this with boneless chicken breasts ( that's all I had in the house) which I brined for an hour, rinsed and dried and then coated with the rub. I then cut it into chunks and followed the recipe from there. But I did add mushrooms and sliced red pepper. The chicken was very moist and tender and the veggies flavorful. But when I make it next I'll probably pump up the seasoning like some other posters mentioned. Maybe fresh ginger and hot sauce. It's definitely worth making and adjusting to your taste.

Rating: 4
This was so excellent! Followed many suggestions here--added powdered ginger to the rub, added sliced red pepper and cremini mushrooms, used chicken broth instead of water--and it came out great. There was a lot of liquid after 25-30 min so I cooked uncovered on very low heat ~20 min and the vegetables became wonderfully caramelized while the chicken remained juicy. Think next time I might use fresh ginger added to the sauce at the end to see how it tastes. Thanks for all the suggestions. This is perfect for guests--rustic and sophisticated at the same time--or for a bunch of frozen meals. I served with quinoa, my favorite grain, and will do so again.

